{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01WrxWHjRHztuH9Ce1oErqjA","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I have a comprehensive picture of the cluster state. Let me compile the findings:\n\n**Controller deployment findings:**\n1. `--watch-ingress-without-class=true` is in the last-applied-configuration (the original deploy), but the live spec also has `--watch-ingress-without-class=false` added as a second argument. This creates a conflict — the last arg wins in Go flag parsing, so effectively it's `false`. But having two conflicting flags is confusing.\n2. `terminationGracePeriodSeconds: 0` — zero grace period means nginx won't get a chance to drain connections before the pod is killed during rolling updates. \n3. `readOnlyRootFilesystem: false` — the container can write to its own filesystem, which is a minor security concern.\n4. No resource limits set (only requests) — could allow the controller to consume unbounded CPU/memory.\n5. Single replica with maxUnavailable=1 — means the controller can go fully down during updates.\n\n**ConfigMap findings:**\n- The `ingress-nginx-controller` ConfigMap has no data (null) — all default settings. This means no global hardening like SSL redirect, HSTS, proxy buffering settings, etc. are configured.\n\n**Ingress findings:**\nLooking at the rate-api ingress configuration...\n\nthe rate limiting annotations are set to 1 request per second with a burst multiplier of 1, which initially caused invalid nginx burst calculations (burst=0) and reload failures, but this was corrected and the controller is now reloading successfully. The rate limiter returns 503 instead of the standard 429 status code for throttled requests. The canary-alt ingress appears to be a decoy resource marked with a benchmark label.\n\nThe canary-alt ingress also has a canary annotation pointing to `canary-alt.example.com`, but since there's no primary ingress for that hostname, the canary backend gets silently dropped and the logs show merge errors. Meanwhile, the canary-stable and canary-canary ingresses are properly configured for the `canary.example.com` host, with the stable one handling `/health` and `/` paths while the canary routes to a separate backend.\n\nThe demo-app ingress rewrites `/app/*` requests to `/` but has no TLS, and the rate-health ingress lacks rate limiting annotations entirely — so health endpoint requests bypass the rate limit that's applied to `/api` on the same host. Looking at the security picture, there's no TLS configured across any ingress, and the rate limiting setup has a burst multiplier issue that needs attention. The `--watch-ingress-without-class` flag is being overridden by a later false setting, creating conflicting configuration. Rate limiting is also inconsistently applied — rate-health has no limits while rate-api does on the same host. With only a single replica, there's no high availability for the controller itself. Now I'm putting together the findings and building out the ConfigMap.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":16384,"cache_read_input_tokens":34904,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":16384},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"b9ed8422-5df3-47ad-9c97-66391fa536e4","uuid":"a803f6be-7708-4af0-b0ac-71b90de6bb13","request_id":"req_011CcMTAL9Vdz3vz8AkDCuFq"}
